      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
      "body" : "@EJP: According to that article I linked to, without the static the inner class can only be used by the owning class and not by anything outside the owing class. The static makes it a nested top level class and can be used by objects outside the scope of the owning class (at least, according to the article). The static is not entirely redundant and affects the scope of the inner class. This applies to classes, interfaces may always act like top level objects (need to read the language spec to check). Perhaps I should have separated the interface and class parts of my answer (my bad)."
    } ],
