    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>In Java, the static interface/class allows the interface/class to be used like a top-level class, that is, it can be declared by other classes. So, you can do:</p>\n\n<pre><code>class Bob\n{\n  void FuncA ()\n  {\n    Foo.Bar foobar;\n  }\n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Without the static, the above would fail to compile. The advantage to this is that you don't need a new source file just to declare the interface. It also visually associates the interface Bar to the class Foo since you have to write Foo.Bar and implies that the Foo class does something with instances of Foo.Bar.</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://www.javaworld.com/javaworld/javaqa/1999-08/01-qa-static2.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">A description of class types in Java</a>.</p>\n"
  }, {
